# **Jack-of-All-Trades — THM — Writeup**

**![5kullk3r][image1]**  
[5kullk3r](https://5kullk3r.medium.com/?source=post_page---byline--029073f45a36---------------------------------------)

6 min read

Hello everyone\! This is an easy room from the TryHackMe platform called **“Jack-of-All-Trades”**. The room is a simple boot-to-root machine with the objective of finding the user flag and then the root flag**.**

My goal is to help you understand each step and provide clear explanations so that anyone, whether a beginner or experienced, can follow along and understand the reasoning behind each action. I hope this write-up makes the process smoother and easier to grasp.

Enough talk — let’s dive right in, and I hope you enjoy the journey\! :)

![][image2]  
No need to have that expression on your face, I know you’re just here for the sauce😹

First, we deploy the machine. While it’s booting up, go ahead and open your terminal tab and get it ready

![][image3]

Once it’s up, let’s paste the IP address and connect to the network. This is what we have in front of us:

However, when encountering the “restricted” error, here’s a quick solution:

* Open a new tab in your browser (in my case, Firefox).  
* Click the **three horizontal lines** in the top-right corner to access the menu.  
* Select **Settings** from the menu.  
* Scroll all the way down to the **Network Settings** section.  
* Click on the **Settings** button next to it.  
* In the settings window, choose the **Manual proxy configuration** option.  
* Enter the desired **IP address** and set the **port number to 22**, as this port is used for HTTP connections.

![][image4]

Then, refresh the page, and you will be directed to the desired destination.

![][image5]

Immediately run **nmap** on the tab and wait for the results, after which I use **feroxbuster** to scan with the following command:

## **feroxbuster \-u [http://10.10.59.210:22/](http://10.10.59.210:22/) \-w /usr/share/wordlists/dirbuster/directory-list-2.3-medium.txt \-x 100**

**![][image6]**

I decided to open the /assets folder in a new tab. To my surprise, I found 4 files listed there.

![][image7]

Then back to the web page, I start by looking through the page but don’t find anything that stands out. So, I decide to hit **Inspect** to dig into the page’s source code.

![][image8]

While inspecting, I spot /**recovery.php** & notice some ***Base64** encoded text* .

I grab the Base64 string and decode it, revealing:  
*"Remember to wish Johny Graves well with his crypto jobhunting\! His encoding systems are amazing\! Also gotta remember your password: u?WtKSraq."*

I try out “Johnny Graves” and “Jack” as usernames with this passwords, but no luck.

![][image9]

So, I go back and inspect the **login page** once more, hoping to find a clue and then I come across another encoded string which on looking tells me it’s a BASE32.

![][image10]

In a hurry, I attempt different decoding methods like ASCII and EBCDIC, but neither works**.**

Then taking a step back, I search online for Johnny Graves’ encoding method, and discover: “First, use **ROT13**, then **Hex**, then **Base32**.

![][image11]

With this info, I drop the Base32 string into **CyberChef** and decode it in the correct order: **Base32 → Hex → ROT13**.

![][image12]

The decoded message gives me a hint:

*“Remember that the credentials to the recovery login are hidden on the homepage\! Here’s a hint: bit.ly/2TvYQ2S”.*

I follow the hint and see **Stegosauria** pop up in the wiki. It also happens to be in the /assets folder as a file called **steg** with an image of a dinosaur.

## **At this point, I start thinking — could it be steganography? ( becasue the word “stego” was there and my 1st task in 1st ever CTF was steg 😂)**

**![][image13]**

I try decoding two images, and finally, **header.jpg** works and I discover the credentials:

![][image14]

***Username**: jackinthebox*

***Password**: TplFxiSHjY*

Using the credentials, I successfully log in to the system, I inspect the page’s source, but there’s nothing useful at first and then notice “GET” in caps, leading me to think it’s a **GET request**.

And, it clearly mentions cmd, which prompts me to toy with the cmd parameter.

*http://10.10.59.210/nnxhweOV/index.php?cmd=id*

* [http://10.10.59.210/nnxhweOV/](http://10.10.59.210/nnxhweOV/)index.php?cmd=ls+-la  
* [http://10.10.59.210/nnxhweOV/](http://10.10.59.210/nnxhweOV/)index.php?cmd=ls+-la+/home  
* [http://10.10.59.210/nnxhweOV/](http://10.10.59.210/nnxhweOV/)index.php?cmd=whoami

The ls command reveals a file named **jacks\_password\_list**.

![][image15]

![][image16]

I use index.php?cmd=cat+/home/jacks\_password\_list to reveal a key hash.

![][image17]

I copy the hash and save it into a text file using nano jak.txt.I then run Hydra to crack the SSH password:

![][image18]

hydra \-l jack \-P jak.txt ssh://10.10.59.210:80

Then, Hydra gives me the login credentials:

* **Username**: jack  
* **Password**: ITMJpGGIqg1jn?\>@

![][image19]

I SSH into the machine using: *ssh jack@10.10.59.210 \-p 80* and then run:

ls \-la to check out the files in the home directory

The user.jpg catches my eye and I run a Python HTTP server

![][image20]

python \-m SimpleHTTPServer 5000

In a new tab, I use wget to download the image:

wget [http://10.10.59.210:5000/user.jpg](http://10.10.59.210:5000/user.jpg)

![][image21]

I open the downloaded image with **eog:**

*eog user.jpg.1*

The **user flag** is visible in the image, I then press **Ctrl \+ C** to stop the initial terminal command.

![][image22]

*securi-tay2020\_{p3ngu1n-hunt3r-3xtr40rd1n41r3}*

I search for **setuid** files using:

*find / \-perm \-u=s \-type f 2\>/dev/null*

I find /usr/bin/strings in the output, I then run strings on the **root flag** file.

*strings /root/root.txt*

*![][image23]*  
Root flag

*securi-tay2020\_{6f125d32f38fb8ff9e720d2dbce2210a}*

*![][image24]*
